DESIGN PRINCIPLE: drift intentionally provides NO command to reset, acknowledge, or dismiss multiple drifted edges at once. `drift reset &lt;marker&gt; &lt;module.spec&gt;` accepts exactly ONE edge per invocation — there is no `--all`, no glob, no multi-arg form, and none will be added. This friction is deliberate and is the whole point of the tool: a bulk reset would let an LLM blindly mark everything as reviewed without actually reviewing the changes, which would make drift useless as a spec-code sync tool. The intended workflow is: `drift todo` (see what broke) → `drift diff --all` (review every broken edge's changes in one pass) → `drift reset &lt;marker&gt; &lt;module.spec&gt;` (resolve ONE edge at a time, after reviewing it). The one-edge-at-a-time reset is the enforcement point: the reset case dispatches to orch.Reset with exactly args[1] (marker) and args[2] (spec) — single strings, never slices.